<span class="displaytext"><b>for immediate release <br/> contact:</b> kevin madden (857) 288-6390 <p><b>boston, ma –</b> today, (candidate last) for president launched its newest radio ad, "stop spending." the ad features senator jim demint (r-sc), a leading voice for fiscal discipline, addressing the need for leadership that will change washington and "end the earmark favor factory." that leadership can only come from governor (candidate full) who has a record of fiscal leadership from outside of washington. </p><p>the ad will begin airing as part of the campaign's rotation today in south carolina. script and viewing links are below. </p><p><b> <u>script for "stop spending" (radio:60):</u> </b> </p><p><b>senator jim demint:</b> "washington politicians call it earmarking, but americans just call it wasteful pork barrel spending, and taxpayers are sick of it. </p><p>"this is senator jim demint, leading the fight to stop wasteful government spending. that's why i need your help to elect a president next year who will force congress to end the earmark favor factory. we need a leader who has the courage and the strength to take on entrenched washington politicians. </p><p>"i believe that leader is (candidate full). mitt is a successful businessman. he's turned around hundreds of companies by cutting waste and leading with new ideas. </p><p>"he used his business skills as governor of massachusetts – issuing over 800 vetoes of wasteful spending and eliminating a $3 billion debt. </p><p>"(candidate full) is the kind of leader america desperately needs. please go to mitt(candidate last).com and help change washington." </p><p><b>governor (candidate full):</b> "i'm (candidate full) and i approved this message." </p><p><b>announcer:</b> "paid for by (candidate last) for president, mitt(candidate last).com." </p><p><em>to listen to "stop spending," please see:</em> <a href="http://www.(candidate full).com/audio/demint.mp3">www.(candidate full).com/audio/demint.mp3</a> </p><p><b> <u>ad facts: script for "stop spending" (radio:60):</u> </b> </p><p><b>senator jim demint:</b> "washington politicians call it earmarking, but americans just call it wasteful pork barrel spending, and taxpayers are sick of it. this is senator jim demint, leading the fight to stop wasteful government spending. that's why i need your help to elect a president next year who will force congress to end the earmark favor factory. we need a leader who has the courage and the strength to take on entrenched washington politicians. i believe that leader is (candidate full)." </p><blockquote dir="ltr" style="margin-right: 0px"> <p><b>- governor (candidate last) will veto appropriations bills that exceed spending targets.</b> he will veto any non-defense appropriations bill that grows spending at a rate greater than inflation minus one percent (cpi-1%). this should be considered the minimum amount of spending reductions. this will save $300 billion over 10 years. ((candidate last) for president, "strategy for a stronger america: a conservative blueprint to strengthen the economy," press release, 10/9/07) </p><p><b>- governor (candidate last) believes the president needs the line-item veto power.</b> as governor, he had line-item authority, and often used it to trim or eliminate individual appropriations. giving the president this power would allow us to make tremendous strides in eliminating earmarks and cutting inefficient programs. ((candidate last) for president, "strategy for a stronger america: a conservative blueprint to strengthen the economy," press release, 10/9/07) </p><p><b>- governor (candidate last) will lead an effort to review and reevaluate all federal spending programs.</b> his administration will undertake an exhaustive review of each individual federal program with the goal to eliminate and consolidate programs that are no longer useful or are bureaucratic and unwieldy. federal spending programs do not have a right to immortality, and should not enjoy automatic increases year after year. ((candidate last) for president, "strategy for a stronger america: a conservative blueprint to strengthen the economy," press release, 10/9/07) </p></blockquote> <p><b>senator jim demint:</b> "mitt is a successful businessman. he's turned around hundreds of companies by cutting waste and leading with new ideas." </p><blockquote dir="ltr" style="margin-right: 0px"> <p><b>- governor (candidate last) has "a solid reputation in the business community for turning companies around."</b> cnn's rhonda schaffler: "(candidate last) had a solid reputation in the business community for turning companies around, like staples, domino's pizza and the sports authority." (cnn's "business unusual," 1/27/02) </p><p><b>- <em>boston business journal</em>: (candidate last) "made his name as a turnaround man."</b> "bain &amp; co. was a crowning victory for (candidate last), 47, who has made his name as a turnaround man. as chief executive of bain capital inc., the venture group he was picked to launch back in 1984, he has backed and helped repair more than 50 companies. with an initial $14 million invested by the partners of bain &amp; co., bain capital has since raised $500 million in four funds, pouring dollars into companies like staples inc., brookstone and the sports authority." (beth healy, "(candidate last) puts skills in business to test," <em>boston business journal</em>, 6/10/94) </p><p><b>- <em>bloomberg</em>'s heidi pryzbyla:</b> "(candidate last)'s business record is unmatched by the current crop of leading candidates." (heidi pryzbyla, "(candidate last) finds classmate bush's management lapses unlikely hurdle," <em>bloomberg</em>, 7/1/07) </p><p><b>- <em>fortune</em>'s marcia vickers:</b> "he is, after all, the most serious major-party presidential candidate to come out of the business world since ... well, since his father, george (candidate last), onetime ceo of american motors, who ran in 1968." (marcia vickers, "the (PARTY NAME)s' mr. fix-it," <em>fortune magazine</em>, 6/27/07) </p><p><b>- <em>the boston globe</em>'s robert gavin and sacha pfeiffer:</b> "in time, (candidate last) would lead the shaky start-up from a staff of seven people managing $37 million to 115 people managing $4 billion in assets. during (candidate last)'s 15-year tenure, bain capital would post an astonishing record, on average doubling its return on realized investments every year." (robert gavin and sacha pfeiffer, "reaping profit in study, sweat," <em>the boston globe</em>, 6/26/07) </p></blockquote> <p><b>senator jim demint:</b> "he used his business skills as governor of massachusetts – issuing over 800 vetoes of wasteful spending and eliminating a $3 billion debt." </p><blockquote dir="ltr" style="margin-right: 0px"> <p><b>- for all four of the fiscal-year budgets that crossed his desk, governor (candidate last) used the line-item veto power more than 800 times.</b> over the course of four budgets, governor (candidate last) made over 300 line-item reductions, 350 line-item eliminations and struck language 150 times. (chapter 26 of the commonwealth of massachusetts acts of 2003, governor's veto message, 6/30/03; chapter 149 of the commonwealth of massachusetts acts of 2004, governor's veto message, 6/25/04; chapter 45 of the commonwealth of massachusetts acts of 2005, governor's veto message, 6/30/05; governor (candidate full), memo to the senate and house of representatives of the commonwealth of massachusetts; fiscal year 2007 general appropriations act veto items: line item accounts, 7/8/06) </p><p><b>- beacon hill institute executive director david terck: "he vetoed hundreds of millions of dollars in spending." (</b>fox news' "journal editorial report," 3/31/07) </p><p><b>- governor (candidate last) closed the nearly $3 billion shortfall without tax increases.</b> "when (candidate full) became governor of massachusetts in 2003, the state had a budget gap of almost $3 billion and was losing thousands of jobs a month. in mr. (candidate last)'s four-year tenure, the deficit was eliminated without raising the sales tax or the income tax, and since the labor slump hit bottom in december 2003, the state has gained 81,000 jobs." (pam belluck, "(candidate last) candidacy puts massachusetts economy in spotlight," <em>the new york times</em>, 3/16/07) </p><p><b>- to close the budget gap, governor (candidate last) forced the legislature to pass "tremendous spending cuts."</b> "governor (candidate last) receives credit for actual spending in fy 2003, even though he entered office halfway into the fiscal year, because of the tremendous spending cuts he forced down the legislature's throat in january of 2003. facing a $650 million deficit he inherited from the previous administration, (candidate last) convinced the unfriendly state legislature to grant him unilateral power to make budget cuts and unveiled $343 million in cuts to cities, healthcare, and state agencies. this fiscal discipline continued in 2004, in which (candidate last) continued to slash 'nearly every part of state government' to close a $3 billion deficit." (the club for growth, "(candidate full)'s record on economic issues," press release, 8/21/07) </p><p><b>- the club for growth: governor (candidate last) "imposed some much-needed fiscal discipline on a very liberal massachusetts legislature."</b> (the club for growth, "(candidate full)'s record on economic issues," press release, 8/21/07) </p></blockquote> <p><b>senator jim demint:</b> "(candidate full) is the kind of leader america desperately needs. please go to mitt(candidate last).com and help change washington." governor (candidate full): "i'm (candidate full) and i approved this message." announcer: "paid for by (candidate last) for president, mitt(candidate last).com." </p><p><em>to listen to "stop spending," please see:</em> <a href="http://www.(candidate full).com/audio/demint.mp3">www.(candidate full).com/audio/demint.mp3</a></p></span>



